and daily practices of liberation enhanced women’s choices in education and occupations. Once the majority of wives and mothers had joined the labor force, by the mid-1980s, new buildings began to emerge that substituted for the unpaid domestic tasks once performed in the home. Fast food franchises, childcare facilities, adult day centers, and hospices were among the inadvertent spatial consequences of the second wave.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aFeminism and architecturezUnited States. 0aFeminismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aFeminist geographyzUnited States. 0aPublic spaceszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban womenzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen and city planningzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aU.S. History. 4aUrban Studies.  afeminism, second wave, segregation, radical activists, women, wives, mothers, labor force.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2016z9783110485332oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170413040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501704130423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501704130/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2016  aZDB-23-DSWb2016